This rating is all about that Classic Italian sandwich. The quality I'm used to from other establishments is basically around some sort of brick oven bread, authentic Italian cold cuts,etc. Amato's was different. It was open-face, with a slight fold lengthwise. It had crisp fresh peppers, sliced olives and some very good quality tomato slices over an excellent combination of cold cuts and provolone. It was more than drizzled with olive oil and vinegar. Adding a couple of sour pickle slices to all this nailed it! The bread was chewy white. Altogether, it's hard to describe how delicious this was.  Eating it felt definitely like a sandwich, but also somehow like pizza, and maybe a little salad. Very satisfying, I look forward to having another on my next trip to Portland!

Just imagine the freshest lobster meat you've ever had tossed with a little mayo and served on a soft Italian roll. I have had lobster rolls all over the city and I would rather pay $12.95 for the lobster roll I had at Amato's than the smaller $16 lobster roll at Eventide. Don't get me wrong, Eventide's brown butter lobster roll is delicious but it's a distant second compared to the one I had at Amato's. Just saying. See for yourself. On another note there was a new cashier who wasn't quite up to speed but the gentleman making the sandwich was super friendly. I ❤️ Amato's.

The basic Maine Italian sandwich -- ham, cheese, sour pickle, onion, tomato, green pepper, olive, s+p+oil on a soft almost doughy sub roll.
